        faqs: [
          { q: "What alimony is a wife entitled to in Saudi Arabia?", a: "Under Saudi Personal Status Law, a wife is entitled to: (1) monthly nafaqa from the date of marriage — covering food, housing, clothing, and medical care — commensurate with the husband's financial capacity; (2) alimony for the full iddah period after divorce (3 months, or until delivery if pregnant); (3) housing rights during the marriage and iddah. The court determines the amount based on the husband's income and assets and the family's accustomed standard of living. Qanoni ensures the full calculation is properly presented to the court." },
          { q: "How is child maintenance calculated in Saudi Arabia?", a: "Child maintenance in Saudi Arabia is determined by the Personal Status Court based on: (1) the father's financial capacity; (2) the child's needs including education, healthcare, and standard of living; (3) the family's customary standard. There is no fixed formula — the court exercises discretion. Qanoni prepares comprehensive financial evidence to support the maximum appropriate maintenance order for your children." },
          { q: "What happens if my husband refuses to pay court-ordered alimony in Saudi Arabia?", a: "Non-payment of court-ordered alimony is enforceable through the Saudi execution courts. Remedies include: salary attachment, bank account attachment, travel ban, and in serious cases, referral to public prosecution. Qanoni moves promptly to enforce alimony orders and pursues all available remedies simultaneously to compel payment." },
          { q: "Can I apply for alimony online in Saudi Arabia?", a: "Yes. Qanoni provides complete online legal consultation and representation for alimony claims. Share your circumstances and relevant financial information via WhatsApp or email, and our family law specialists will advise on your entitlements and file your claim through the MASAR system. No office visit required — and complete confidentiality is maintained throughout." },
        ],
