        overview1: "Precautionary asset attachment — the legal power to freeze a debtor's assets before a final judgment is obtained — is one of the most powerful and time-sensitive tools available to creditors in Saudi Arabia. Under Saudi procedural law and the Saudi Enforcement Law, courts have authority to order the attachment of bank accounts, real estate, vehicles, commercial assets, and shares in companies on an urgent, ex-parte basis — provided the applicant can demonstrate an apparent right and the risk that recovery will be frustrated without immediate attachment. Acting quickly is critical: once a debtor learns that proceedings are being prepared, assets can be rapidly transferred or dissipated. Qanoni moves with urgency — filing precautionary attachment applications before the appropriate Saudi court as a first-response measure in any significant commercial or personal debt dispute.",
        overview2: "Precautionary attachment is not only available to secure debts already due — it can also be sought in anticipation of a judgment in ongoing litigation, to preserve the enforceability of an expected award, or to secure assets in connection with fraud, misrepresentation, and unjust enrichment claims. Understanding which assets to target, which court to apply to, and what evidence is needed to satisfy the legal test for attachment is essential to a successful application. Qanoni advises immediately on the availability of attachment and moves without delay to file.",
