      "criminal-investigations": {
        title: "Criminal Investigations",
        seoTitle: "Criminal Investigation Lawyer in Saudi Arabia — Public Prosecution Representation & Rights Protection",
        subtitle: "Expert representation during criminal investigation stage — protecting your rights before the Saudi Public Prosecution and law enforcement.",
        overview1: "The investigation stage of a criminal case in Saudi Arabia — conducted by the Public Prosecution (al-Idda'a al-'Amma) — is a critical phase that shapes the entire course of the case. Evidence collected during investigation, statements made by accused persons, and procedural decisions taken at this stage all directly affect the outcome of any subsequent prosecution. Accused persons have legal rights during investigation — including the right to silence and the right to legal representation — but these rights must be actively asserted to be effective.",
        overview2: "At Qanoni, we represent clients at the investigation stage of criminal cases — advising on the right to silence, attending investigative sessions, challenging unlawful detention, and managing the presentation of our client's position to the Public Prosecution. Early intervention at the investigation stage often provides the best opportunity to limit criminal exposure — and in some cases to prevent a formal charge being brought at all.",
        experienceNote: "Qanoni's early intervention in the criminal investigation stage has in many cases resulted in cases being closed without formal charge, or in a significant limitation of the charges ultimately brought. The investigation stage is where defense strategy is most effective — and Qanoni's 30+ years of experience advising clients from the moment of first contact with law enforcement gives every client the strongest possible start.",
        covers: ["Public Prosecution investigation stage representation", "Rights protection during interrogation and questioning", "Advice on right to silence and self-incrimination", "Challenge of unlawful arrest and detention", "Bail and release applications during investigation", "Evidence preservation and documentation", "Liaison with Public Prosecution on investigation timeline", "Defense preparation for prosecution decision"],
        process: [
          { title: "Immediate Engagement", desc: "We engage immediately on any contact with law enforcement or the Public Prosecution — advising on your rights, the nature of the investigation, and the appropriate response to investigative inquiries." },
          { title: "Investigation Stage Representation", desc: "We attend all investigative sessions with the Public Prosecution, assert your procedural rights, ensure questioning is conducted lawfully, and present your position clearly on the record." },
          { title: "Evidence Management", desc: "We advise on the preservation of evidence favorable to your defense, challenge unlawfully obtained evidence, and manage the disclosure of information to the prosecution in the most favorable way." },
          { title: "Pre-charge Strategy", desc: "We present submissions to the Public Prosecution seeking either closure of the case without charge or limitation of the charges — and prepare comprehensively for any trial if charges are ultimately brought." },
        ],
        faqs: [
          { q: "Do I have to answer questions from Saudi law enforcement?", a: "The right to silence — the right not to incriminate yourself — exists in Saudi criminal procedure, although its precise scope differs from common-law systems. Accused persons are not required to confess or provide self-incriminating answers. However, remaining silent must be handled carefully and in context, as unhelpful responses can sometimes create negative impressions. Qanoni advises clients specifically on how to respond (or not respond) to investigative questioning in each specific case." },
          { q: "Can the police arrest me without a warrant in Saudi Arabia?", a: "Saudi law generally requires an arrest warrant from the Public Prosecution, except in flagrante delicto cases (where the offense is witnessed in the act) or cases involving serious offenses where the law permits arrest without prior authorization. Arrest without warrant in circumstances not permitted by law can give rise to a challenge to the lawfulness of detention and the admissibility of evidence obtained thereafter. Qanoni advises on whether any arrest or detention was unlawful and pursues appropriate remedies." },
          { q: "What should I do if I receive a summons from the Public Prosecution in Saudi Arabia?", a: "You should obtain legal advice immediately — before attending any session with the Public Prosecution. A summons from the Public Prosecution indicates you are under investigation and may face criminal charges. The advice you receive before attending will shape how you present yourself and what information you provide. Qanoni advises clients who receive Public Prosecution summonses on an emergency basis and accompanies them to all investigation stage sessions." },
        ],
      },
