      "data-protection": {
        title: "Data Protection & PDPL",
        seoTitle: "Data Protection Lawyer in Saudi Arabia — PDPL Compliance & Personal Data Law Advice",
        subtitle: "Expert advice on Saudi Arabia's Personal Data Protection Law (PDPL) — compliance programs, regulatory investigations, and data breach response.",
        overview1: "Saudi Arabia's Personal Data Protection Law (Royal Decree M/19, 2021) — enforced by the National Data Management Office (NDMO) and the Saudi Data and Artificial Intelligence Authority (SDAIA) — imposes comprehensive obligations on organizations that collect, process, or transfer personal data of Saudi residents. The PDPL requires lawful basis for processing, privacy notices, data subject rights procedures, data breach notification, and in some cases data protection impact assessments. Violations carry administrative fines and in serious cases criminal penalties.",
        overview2: "At Qanoni, our data protection practice covers PDPL compliance advisory, data protection impact assessments, regulatory investigation defense, and data breach response. We help organizations build PDPL-compliant data processing frameworks — including privacy policies, consent mechanisms, data subject rights procedures, and vendor data processing agreements — and advise on regulatory engagement when data breaches or complaints arise.",
        experienceNote: "Qanoni's data protection practice provides PDPL compliance advice for Saudi and international organizations processing personal data in Saudi Arabia. Saudi Arabia's PDPL is still relatively new and the regulatory enforcement approach is evolving — specialist legal advice is essential to navigate compliance requirements and regulatory engagement effectively.",
        covers: ["PDPL compliance assessment and gap analysis", "Privacy policy and notice drafting", "Data processing agreement preparation", "Data subject rights procedure implementation", "Data protection impact assessments (DPIA)", "Data breach notification and response", "NDMO regulatory investigation defense", "Cross-border data transfer compliance advice"],
        process: [
          { title: "PDPL Compliance Assessment", desc: "We assess your organization's PDPL compliance position — mapping personal data flows, identifying legal bases for processing, and documenting gaps between current practices and PDPL requirements." },
          { title: "Compliance Program", desc: "We develop and implement a PDPL compliance program — including privacy policies, consent mechanisms, data subject rights procedures, vendor agreements, and staff training." },
          { title: "Breach Response", desc: "When a personal data breach occurs, we provide immediate response advice — assessing notification obligations, managing NDMO notification, and advising on remediation measures." },
          { title: "Regulatory Defense", desc: "When NDMO initiates a regulatory investigation or enforcement action, we represent the organization — managing regulatory engagement, presenting the compliance position, and challenging any proposed sanctions." },
        ],
        faqs: [
          { q: "Who does the PDPL apply to?", a: "The Saudi PDPL applies to any organization — Saudi or foreign — that processes the personal data of Saudi residents, regardless of where the organization is located. This means that international companies with Saudi customers, employees, or other data subjects may be subject to the PDPL even without a physical presence in Saudi Arabia. Qanoni advises on the specific PDPL obligations applicable to each organization's data processing activities." },
          { q: "What are the penalties for PDPL violations in Saudi Arabia?", a: "Administrative fines for PDPL violations can reach SAR 5 million, with doubled penalties for repeat offenses. Intentional misuse of personal data for personal gain or to cause harm carries criminal penalties — including imprisonment. In addition to regulatory penalties, data subjects may have private law claims arising from misuse of their personal data. Qanoni advises on PDPL penalty exposure and implements compliance measures to minimize the risk of regulatory action." },
          { q: "Does the PDPL require data breach notification?", a: "Yes. Organizations subject to the PDPL must notify SDAIA of data breaches that could harm data subjects — within a defined notification period. The notification must include specified information about the breach, its scope, and the remediation measures taken. Data subjects must also be notified in certain circumstances. Qanoni provides immediate data breach response advice and manages the SDAIA notification process." },
        ],
      },
