      "hacking-defense": {
        title: "Hacking & Unauthorized Access",
        seoTitle: "Hacking Defense Lawyer in Saudi Arabia — Unauthorized Access & Cybersecurity Breach Defense",
        subtitle: "Expert criminal defense for hacking and unauthorized access charges under Saudi Arabia's Anti-Cybercrime Law.",
        overview1: "Hacking — accessing computer systems, networks, or data without authorization — is criminalized under Article 3 of Saudi Arabia's Anti-Cybercrime Law (Royal Decree M/17). Penalties range from SAR 500,000 and 1 year imprisonment for basic unauthorized access to SAR 5 million and 4 years imprisonment for access to government or financial institution systems. Cybersecurity incidents that CITC investigates can quickly escalate from technical matters to criminal investigations, and early legal intervention is essential.",
        overview2: "At Qanoni, our hacking defense practice provides expert representation for individuals and organizations accused of unauthorized access or hacking under the Anti-Cybercrime Law. We challenge the technical evidence on which hacking charges are based, advise on the authorization question (whether access was lawful), and develop comprehensive defenses addressing every element of the prosecution's case.",
        experienceNote: "Defending hacking charges requires a combination of criminal law expertise and technical understanding of how digital forensic evidence is collected and challenged. Qanoni's cybercrime defense team has experience defending unauthorized access cases across multiple categories — corporate network access disputes, social media account access, and government system access cases — providing technically informed defense at every stage.",
        covers: ["Unauthorized access defense (Anti-Cybercrime Law Art. 3)", "Corporate network intrusion defense", "Social media account unauthorized access defense", "Government system access defense", "Financial system access defense", "Digital forensic evidence challenge", "Cybersecurity incident criminal defense", "Authorized access scope dispute defense"],
        process: [
          { title: "Emergency Legal Assessment", desc: "We assess the hacking allegation immediately — reviewing the specific conduct alleged, the authorization question, and the digital evidence relied upon to determine the strongest available defenses." },
          { title: "Technical Evidence Analysis", desc: "We analyze all digital forensic evidence in detail — challenging collection methodology, chain of custody, and technical interpretation with the assistance of independent technical experts." },
          { title: "Authorization Defense", desc: "We develop the authorization defense — demonstrating that the access was authorized, that the authorization exceeded the scope alleged, or that the specific technical conduct does not constitute access within the meaning of the law." },
          { title: "Trial Defense & Appeals", desc: "We represent you fully at all criminal court hearings and pursue appeals against any conviction with expert appellate advocacy and technical expert support." },
        ],
        faqs: [
          { q: "Is it a crime to access an unsecured computer system in Saudi Arabia?", a: "Yes. The Anti-Cybercrime Law does not require that a system be password-protected or secured for unauthorized access to be criminal — the offense is defined by the absence of authorization from the system owner, regardless of whether technical security measures were in place. However, the existence of active security measures that were bypassed is an aggravating factor in prosecution. Qanoni advises on the specific authorization question in each hacking case." },
          { q: "Can a company sue an employee for accessing company systems without authorization?", a: "Yes. An employee who exceeds their authorized access to company systems — accessing files, systems, or data outside the scope of their role — can face both criminal prosecution under the Anti-Cybercrime Law and civil liability to the company. Employment contracts often include specific provisions on authorized system access. Qanoni advises on the scope of employee authorization and represents both companies and employees in system access disputes." },
          { q: "What is the defense of authorization in a hacking case?", a: "The central defense in many hacking cases is that the accused had authorization — express or implied — for the access alleged. Authorization can arise from: express written permission from the system owner; implied permission from the nature of the relationship between the accused and the system owner; or the public availability of the data or system accessed. Qanoni analyzes the authorization question carefully in every unauthorized access case and develops the strongest available authorization arguments." },
        ],
      },
